# 1-bit Full Adder from NAND gates
#
# This chip adds three 1-bit numbers (A, B, Carry-In) and produces a 2-bit result (Sum, Carry-Out).
# It is constructed from 9 NAND gates.
# Adheres to the rule that general-purpose RAM starts at address 16.
#
# --- Memory Map ---
# Inputs:
#   RAM[30]: Input A
#   RAM[31]: Input B
#   RAM[32]: Input Cin
#
# Outputs:
#   RAM[40]: Sum
#   RAM[41]: Cout
#
# Intermediate Values:
#   RAM[51] - RAM[57]: Temporary results from NAND gates.

# 1. n1 = NAND(A, B) -> ram[51]
0000000000000001 0000000000110011 0000000000011110 0000000000011111

# 2. n2 = NAND(A, n1) -> ram[52]
0000000000000001 0000000000110100 0000000000011110 0000000000110011

# 3. n3 = NAND(B, n1) -> ram[53]
0000000000000001 0000000000110101 0000000000011111 0000000000110011

# 4. n4 = NAND(n2, n3) -> ram[54]  (This is A XOR B)
0000000000000001 0000000000110110 0000000000110100 0000000000110101

# 5. n5 = NAND(n4, Cin) -> ram[55]
0000000000000001 0000000000110111 0000000000110110 0000000000100000

# 6. n6 = NAND(n4, n5) -> ram[56]
0000000000000001 0000000000111000 0000000000110110 0000000000110111

# 7. n7 = NAND(Cin, n5) -> ram[57]
0000000000000001 0000000000111001 0000000000100000 0000000000110111

# 8. Sum = NAND(n6, n7) -> ram[40]
0000000000000001 0000000000101000 0000000000111000 0000000000111001

# 9. Cout = NAND(n1, n5) -> ram[41]
0000000000000001 0000000000101001 0000000000110011 0000000000110111
